    <section>
        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>The U.S. visa sponsorship program has expanded significantly in 2025, offering pathways for employment, education, and family reunification. With heightened competition, understanding eligibility criteria, application strategies, and sponsor responsibilities is critical.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Types of Visa Sponsorship</h2>
        
        <h3>1. Family-Based Sponsorship</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>For spouses, parents, or siblings of U.S. citizens/permanent residents</li>
            <li>Requires proof of relationship and financial stability</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Employment-Based Sponsorship</h3>
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Visa Type</th>
                <th>Eligibility</th>
                <th>Common Fields</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>H-1B</td>
                <td>Bachelor’s degree+</td>
                <td>IT, Engineering, Finance</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>L-1</td>
                <td>Intra-company transfer</td>
                <td>Multinational employees</td>
            </tr>
        </table>

        <div class="tip-box">
            <strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Consult an immigration attorney to match your profile with the ideal visa category.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>How to Apply</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Determine eligibility for your preferred visa type</li>
            <li>Secure a sponsor (employer or family member)</li>
            <li>Submit required documentation (passport, forms, certificates)</li>
            <li>Attend interviews (consulate or USCIS)</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

